[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In graph theory and computer science, an **adjacency matrix** is a square matrix used to represent a finite graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The elements of the matrix indicate whether pairs of vertices are adjacent or not within the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In the special case of a finite simple graph, the adjacency matrix is a (0,1)-matrix with zeros on its diagonal.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] If the graph is undirected (i.e. all of its edges are bidirectional), the adjacency matrix is symmetric.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The relationship between a graph and the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of its adjacency matrix is studied in spectral graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a graph should be distinguished from its incidence matrix, a different matrix representation whose elements indicate whether vertex–edge pairs are incident or not, and its degree matrix, which contains information about the degree of each vertex.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] For a simple graph with vertex set *U* = {*u*1, ..., *u**n*}, the adjacency matrix is a square *n* × *n* matrix A such that its element Aij is 1 when there is an edge from vertex *u*i to vertex *u*j, and 0 when there is no edge.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The diagonal elements of the matrix are all 0, since edges from a vertex to itself (loops) are not allowed in simple graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] It is also sometimes useful in algebraic graph theory to replace the nonzero elements with algebraic variables.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The same concept can be extended to multigraphs and graphs with loops by storing the number of edges between each two vertices in the corresponding matrix element, and by allowing nonzero diagonal elements.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Loops may be counted either once (as a single edge) or twice (as two vertex-edge incidences), as long as a consistent convention is followed.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Undirected graphs often use the latter convention of counting loops twice, whereas directed graphs typically use the former convention.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] where B is an *r* × *s* matrix, and 0*r*,*r* and 0*s*,*s* represent the *r* × *r* and *s* × *s* zero matrices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In this case, the smaller matrix B uniquely represents the graph, and the remaining parts of A can be discarded as redundant.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] B is sometimes called the *biadjacency matrix*.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The biadjacency matrix is the *r* × *s* 0–1 matrix B in which *b**i*,*j* = 1 if and only if (*u**i*, *v**j*) ∈ *E*.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] If G is a bipartite multigraph or weighted graph, then the elements b*i,j* are taken to be the number of edges between the vertices or the weight of the edge (*u**i*, *v**j*), respectively.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] An (*a*, *b*, *c*)-adjacency matrix A of a simple graph has *A**i*,*j* = *a* if (*i*, *j*) is an edge, b if it is not, and c on the diagonal.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The Seidel adjacency matrix is a (−1, 1, 0)-adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] This matrix is used in studying strongly regular graphs and two-graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix has in position (*i*, *j*) the distance between vertices vi and vj.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The distance is the length of a shortest path connecting the vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Unless lengths of edges are explicitly provided, the length of a path is the number of edges in it.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix resembles a high power of the adjacency matrix, but instead of telling only whether or not two vertices are connected (i.e., the connection matrix, which contains Boolean values), it gives the exact distance between them.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The convention followed here (for undirected graphs) is that each edge adds 1 to the appropriate cell in the matrix, and each loop (an edge from a vertex to itself) adds 2 to the appropriate cell on the diagonal in the matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] This allows the degree of a vertex to be easily found by taking the sum of the values in either its respective row or column in the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph can be asymmetric.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The former definition is commonly used in graph theory and social network analysis (e.g., sociology, political science, economics, psychology).
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The latter is more common in other applied sciences (e.g., dynamical systems, physics, network science) where A is sometimes used to describe linear dynamics on graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Using the first definition, the in-degrees of a vertex can be computed by summing the entries of the corresponding column and the out-degree of vertex by summing the entries of the corresponding row.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] When using the second definition, the in-degree of a vertex is given by the corresponding row sum and the out-degree is given by the corresponding column sum.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a complete graph contains all ones except along the diagonal where there are only zeros.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an empty graph is a zero matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an undirected simple graph is symmetric, and therefore has a complete set of real eigenvalues and an orthogonal eigenvector basis.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The set of eigenvalues of a graph is the **spectrum** of the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The greatest eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ is bounded above by the maximum degree.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] This can be seen as result of the Perron–Frobenius theorem, but it can be proved easily.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Let v be one eigenvector associated to $\lambda _{1}$ and x the entry in which v has maximum absolute value.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Without loss of generality assume vx is positive since otherwise you simply take the eigenvector -v, also associated to $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] For d-regular graphs, d is the first eigenvalue of A for the vector *v* = (1, ..., 1) (it is easy to check that it is an eigenvalue and it is the maximum because of the above bound).
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The multiplicity of this eigenvalue is the number of connected components of G, in particular $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}$ for connected graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] It can be shown that for each eigenvalue $\lambda _{i}$ , its opposite $-\lambda _{i}=\lambda _{n+1-i}$ is also an eigenvalue of A if G is a bipartite graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In particular −d is an eigenvalue of any d-regular bipartite graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The difference $\lambda _{1}-\lambda _{2}$ is called the spectral gap and it is related to the expansion of G.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] It is also useful to introduce the spectral radius of A denoted by $\lambda (G)=\max _{\left|\lambda _{i}\right|<d}|\lambda _{i}|$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] This bound is tight in the Ramanujan graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Suppose two directed or undirected graphs *G*1 and *G*2 with adjacency matrices *A*1 and *A*2 are given.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In particular, *A*1 and *A*2 are similar and therefore have the same minimal polynomial, characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, determinant and trace.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] These can therefore serve as isomorphism invariants of graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] However, two graphs may possess the same set of eigenvalues but not be isomorphic.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Such linear operators are said to be isospectral.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] If A is the adjacency matrix of the directed or undirected graph G, then the matrix *A**n* (i.e., the matrix product of n copies of A) has an interesting interpretation: the element (*i*, *j*) gives the number of (directed or undirected) walks of length n from vertex i to vertex j.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] If n is the smallest nonnegative integer, such that for some i, j, the element (*i*, *j*) of *A**n* is positive, then n is the distance between vertex i and vertex j.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] A great example of how this is useful is in counting the number of triangles in an undirected graph G, which is exactly the trace of *A*3 divided by 3 or 6 depending on whether the graph is directed or not.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] We divide by those values to compensate for the overcounting of each triangle.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In an undirected graph, each triangle will be counted twice for all three nodes, because the path can be followed clockwise or counterclockwise : ijk or ikj.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix can be used to determine whether or not the graph is connected.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] If a directed graph has a nilpotent adjacency matrix (i.e., if there exists n such that *A**n* is the zero matrix), then it is a directed acyclic graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix may be used as a data structure for the representation of graphs in computer programs for manipulating graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Boolean data types are used, such as `True` and `False` in Python.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The main alternative data structure, also in use for this application, is the adjacency list.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] The space needed to represent an adjacency matrix and the time needed to perform operations on them is dependent on the matrix representation chosen for the underlying matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Sparse matrix representations only store non-zero matrix entries and implicitly represent the zero entries.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] They can, for example, be used to represent sparse graphs without incurring the space overhead from storing the many zero entries in the adjacency matrix of the sparse graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] In the following section the adjacency matrix is assumed to be represented by an array data structure so that zero and non-zero entries are all directly represented in storage.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Although slightly more succinct representations are possible, this method gets close to the information-theoretic lower bound for the minimum number of bits needed to represent all n-vertex graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] For storing graphs in text files, fewer bits per byte can be used to ensure that all bytes are text characters, for instance by using a Base64 representation.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Besides avoiding wasted space, this compactness encourages locality of reference.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] However, for a large sparse graph, adjacency lists require less storage space, because they do not waste any space representing edges that are *not* present.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] An alternative form of adjacency matrix (which, however, requires a larger amount of space) replaces the numbers in each element of the matrix with pointers to edge objects (when edges are present) or null pointers (when there is no edge).
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] It is also possible to store edge weights directly in the elements of an adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Besides the space tradeoff, the different data structures also facilitate different operations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] Finding all vertices adjacent to a given vertex in an adjacency list is as simple as reading the list, and takes time proportional to the number of neighbors.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] With an adjacency matrix, an entire row must instead be scanned, which takes a larger amount of time, proportional to the number of vertices in the whole graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/adjacency-matrix] On the other hand, testing whether there is an edge between two given vertices can be determined at once with an adjacency matrix, while requiring time proportional to the minimum degree of the two vertices with the adjacency list.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Because graphs usually do not have a canonical ordering of their nodes, GNN architectures are commonly designed to be permutation equivariant: reordering the nodes in the input reorders the corresponding node representations in the same way.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] For graph-level prediction tasks, GNNs typically use a permutation-invariant readout function, whose output is unchanged by the ordering of the nodes.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A prominent example is molecular drug design.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Molecules can be represented as graphs, with nodes for atoms and edges for atomic bonds, often including known chemical properties as features.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Inputs may thus differ in size, due to varying number of atoms and bonds.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A graph-level task may be to predict the efficacy of a given molecule for a specific medical application, such as eliminating *E. coli* bacteria.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The key design element of GNNs is the use of *pairwise message passing*, such that graph nodes iteratively update their representations by exchanging information with their neighbors.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Several GNN architectures have been proposed, which implement different flavors of message passing, started by recursive or convolutional constructive approaches.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A 2022 position paper argued that many architectures described as going "beyond" message passing can instead be interpreted as message passing over suitably modified graphs, and proposed the term "augmented message passing" for such approaches.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In the more general subject of "geometric deep learning", certain existing neural network architectures can be interpreted as GNNs operating on suitably defined graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A convolutional neural network layer, in the context of computer vision, can be considered a GNN applied to graphs whose nodes are pixels, and only adjacent pixels are connected by edges in the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A transformer layer, in natural language processing, can be considered a GNN applied to complete graphs whose nodes are words or tokens in a passage of natural language text.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Relevant application domains for GNNs include natural language processing, social networks, citation networks, molecular biology, chemistry, physics and NP-hard combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Open source libraries implementing GNNs include PyTorch Geometric (PyTorch), TensorFlow GNN (TensorFlow), Deep Graph Library (framework agnostic), jraph (Google JAX), and GraphNeuralNetworks.jl/GeometricFlux.jl (Julia, Flux).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] *Local pooling*: a local pooling layer coarsens the graph via downsampling.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Local pooling is used to increase the receptive field of a GNN, in a similar fashion to pooling layers in convolutional neural networks.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Examples include k-nearest neighbours pooling, top-k pooling, and self-attention pooling.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] *Global pooling*: a global pooling layer, also known as *readout* layer, provides fixed-size representation of the whole graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The global pooling layer must be permutation invariant, such that permutations in the ordering of graph nodes and edges do not alter the final output.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Examples include element-wise sum, mean or maximum.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Standard message-passing GNNs are at most as expressive as the Weisfeiler Leman graph isomorphism test.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In practice, this means that there exist different graph structures that cannot be distinguished by GNNs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] More powerful GNNs operating on higher-dimension geometries such as simplicial complexes can be designed.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] As of 2022, whether or not future architectures will overcome the message passing primitive is an open research question.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Message passing layers are permutation-equivariant layers mapping a graph into an updated representation of the same graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Formally, they can be expressed as message passing neural networks (MPNNs).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Let $G=(V,E)$ be a graph, where V is the node set and E is the edge set.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Let $N_{u}$ be the neighbourhood of some node $u\in V$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Additionally, let $\mathbf {x} _{u}$ be the features of node $u\in V$ , and $\mathbf {e} _{uv}$ be the features of edge $(u,v)\in E$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] where $\phi$ and $\psi$ are differentiable functions (e.g., artificial neural networks), and $\bigoplus$ is a permutation invariant aggregation operator that can accept an arbitrary number of inputs (e.g., element-wise sum, mean, or max).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In particular, $\phi$ and $\psi$ are referred to as *update* and *message* functions, respectively.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Intuitively, in an MPNN computational block, graph nodes *update* their representations by *aggregating* the *messages* received from their neighbours.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The outputs of one or more MPNN layers are node representations $\mathbf {h} _{u}$ for each node $u\in V$ in the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Node representations can be employed for any downstream task, such as node/graph classification or edge prediction.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Graph nodes in an MPNN update their representation aggregating information from their immediate neighbours.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] As such, stacking n MPNN layers means that one node will be able to communicate with nodes that are at most n "hops" away.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In principle, to ensure that every node receives information from every other node, one would need to stack a number of MPNN layers equal to the graph diameter.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] However, stacking many MPNN layers may cause issues such as oversmoothing and oversquashing.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Oversmoothing refers to the issue of node representations becoming indistinguishable.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Oversquashing refers to the bottleneck that is created by squeezing long-range dependencies into fixed-size representations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Countermeasures such as skip connections (as in residual neural networks), gated update rules and jumping knowledge can mitigate oversmoothing.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Modifying the final layer to be a fully-adjacent layer, i.e., by considering the graph as a complete graph, can mitigate oversquashing in problems where long-range dependencies are required.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Other "flavours" of MPNN have been developed in the literature, such as graph convolutional networks and graph attention networks, whose definitions can be expressed in terms of the MPNN formalism.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The graph convolutional network (GCN) was first introduced by Thomas Kipf and Max Welling in 2017.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A GCN layer defines a first-order approximation of a localized spectral filter on graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GCNs can be understood as a generalization of convolutional neural networks to graph-structured data.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In particular, let $\mathbf {A}$ be the graph adjacency matrix: then, one can define ${\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}=\mathbf {A} +\mathbf {I}$ and ${\tilde {\mathbf {D} }}_{ii}=\sum _{j\in V}{\tilde {A}}_{ij}$ , where $\mathbf {I}$ denotes the identity matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] This normalization ensures that the eigenvalues of ${\tilde {\mathbf {D} }}^{-{\frac {1}{2}}}{\tilde {\mathbf {A} }}{\tilde {\mathbf {D} }}^{-{\frac {1}{2}}}$ are bounded in the range $[0,1]$ , avoiding numerical instabilities and exploding/vanishing gradients.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A limitation of GCNs is that they do not allow multidimensional edge features $\mathbf {e} _{uv}$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] It is however possible to associate scalar weights $w_{uv}$ to each edge by imposing $A_{uv}=w_{uv}$ , i.e., by setting each nonzero entry in the adjacency matrix equal to the weight of the corresponding edge.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The graph attention network (GAT) was introduced by Petar Veličković et al. in 2018.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A graph attention network is a combination of a GNN and an attention layer.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The implementation of attention layer in graphical neural networks helps provide attention or focus to the important information from the data instead of focusing on the whole data.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] For the final GAT layer, the outputs from each attention head are averaged before the application of the activation function.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Attention in Machine Learning is a technique that mimics cognitive attention.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In the context of learning on graphs, the attention coefficient $\alpha _{uv}$ measures *how important* node v is to node u .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] where $\mathbf {a}$ is a vector of learnable weights, $\cdot ^{T}$ indicates transposition, $\mathbf {e} _{uv}$ are the edge features (if present), and ${\text{LeakyReLU}}$ is a modified ReLU activation function.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Attention coefficients are then normalized via softmax to make them easily comparable across different nodes.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A GCN can be seen as a special case of a GAT where attention coefficients are not learnable, but fixed and equal to the edge weights $w_{uv}$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The gated graph sequence neural network (GGS-NN) was introduced by Yujia Li et al. in 2015.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The GGS-NN extends the GNN formulation by Scarselli et al. to output sequences.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The message passing framework is implemented as an update rule to a gated recurrent unit (GRU) cell.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] where $\Vert$ denotes vector concatenation, $\mathbf {0}$ is a vector of zeros, $\mathbf {\Theta }$ is a matrix of learnable parameters, ${\text{GRU}}$ is a GRU cell, and l denotes the sequence index.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In a GGS-NN, the node representations are regarded as the hidden states of a GRU cell.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The initial node features $\mathbf {x} _{u}^{(0)}$ are zero-padded up to the hidden state dimension of the GRU cell.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The same GRU cell is used for updating representations for each node.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Local pooling layers, transform a graph into a smaller coarsened graph before subsequent message-passing or readout layers.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In contrast to global pooling, which aggregates all node representations into a single graph-level representation, local pooling produces an intermediate graph with its own node-feature matrix and adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In each case, the input is a graph represented by a node-feature matrix $\mathbf {X}$ and an adjacency matrix $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The output is a coarsened node-feature matrix $\mathbf {X} '$ and a coarsened adjacency matrix $\mathbf {A} '$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Differentiable pooling, or DiffPool, is a node-clustering pooling method introduced in 2018.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Instead of selecting a subset of the original nodes, DiffPool learns a soft assignment of nodes to clusters (by using scores between 0 and 1).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] These clusters become the nodes of the coarsened graph used by the next GNN layer.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Given a node-feature matrix $\mathbf {X}$ and an adjacency matrix $\mathbf {A}$ , DiffPool uses two graph neural networks.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] where $S_{ij}$ denotes the soft assignment of node i to cluster j .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In this formulation, each new node in $\mathbf {X} '$ represents a learned cluster of nodes from the previous graph, and edges in $\mathbf {A} '$ represent aggregate connectivity between clusters.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Because the assignment matrix is differentiable, DiffPool can be trained end-to-end together with the surrounding GNN layers.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The original formulation additionally introduced auxiliary losses to encourage nearby nodes to be assigned to similar clusters and to encourage confident cluster assignments.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] We first set $\mathbf {y} ={\frac {\mathbf {X} \mathbf {p} }{\Vert \mathbf {p} \Vert }}$ where $\mathbf {p}$ is a learnable projection vector that computes a scalar projection value for each node.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] where $\mathbf {i} ={\text{top}}_{k}(\mathbf {y} )$ is the subset of nodes with the top-k highest projection scores, $\odot$ denotes element-wise matrix multiplication, and ${\text{sigmoid}}(\cdot )$ is the sigmoid function.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In other words, the nodes with the top-k highest projection scores are retained in the new adjacency matrix $\mathbf {A} '$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The ${\text{sigmoid}}(\cdot )$ operation makes the projection vector $\mathbf {p}$ trainable by backpropagation, which otherwise would produce discrete outputs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] where $\mathbf {i} ={\text{top}}_{k}(\mathbf {y} )$ is the subset of nodes with the top-k highest projection scores, $\odot$ denotes element-wise matrix multiplication.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The self-attention pooling layer can be seen as an extension of the top-k pooling layer.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Differently from top-k pooling, the self-attention scores computed in self-attention pooling account both for the graph features and the graph topology.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The homophily principle, i.e., nodes with the same labels or similar attributes are more likely to be connected, has been commonly believed to be the main reason for the superiority of GNNs over traditional Neural Networks (NNs) on graph-structured data, especially on node-level tasks.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] However, recent work has identified a non-trivial set of datasets where GNN's performance compared to the NN's is not satisfactory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Heterophily, i.e., low homophily, has been considered the main cause of this empirical observation.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] People have begun to revisit and re-evaluate most existing graph models in the heterophily scenario across various kinds of graphs, e.g., heterogeneous graphs, temporal graphs and hypergraphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] In the past few years, considerable effort has been devoted to studying and addressing the heterophily issue in graph learning.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Training GNNs on large graphs presents computational challenges that differ substantially from those in other neural network architectures.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Two broad problem settings arise: training on a single very large graph (such as a social network with billions of nodes), and training on collections of large individual graphs (such as molecular systems requiring higher-order interaction modeling).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] For the single large graph setting, sampling-based methods reduce memory requirements by operating on subgraphs rather than the full graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Cluster-GCN partitions the graph into subgraphs using graph partitioning algorithms, training the model on each partition in sequence.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GraphSAINT instead samples subgraphs stochastically during training, constructing unbiased estimators for the full graph loss.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Distributed frameworks such as DistDGL extend training to multi-machine settings, managing the inter-machine communication required for neighborhood aggregation when a graph's nodes are distributed across machines.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] **Graph Parallelism** addresses this by distributing a single input graph across multiple GPUs, partitioning nodes and edges across devices rather than distributing samples across devices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] This approach enabled GNNs with hundreds of millions to billions of parameters to be trained on atomic systems that would otherwise exceed single-device memory, and has been applied to the development of large-scale universal interatomic potentials.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Social networks are a major application domain for GNNs due to their natural representation as social graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GNNs are used to develop recommender systems based on both social relations and item relations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GNNs are used as fundamental building blocks for several combinatorial optimization algorithms.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Examples include computing shortest paths or Eulerian circuits for a given graph, deriving chip placements superior or competitive to handcrafted human solutions, and improving expert-designed branching rules in branch and bound.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] When viewed as a graph, a network of computers can be analyzed with GNNs for anomaly detection.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Anomalies within provenance graphs often correlate to malicious activity within the network.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GNNs have been used to identify these anomalies on individual nodes and within paths to detect malicious processes, or on the edge level to detect lateral movement.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Water distribution systems can be modeled as graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GNNs have been applied to water demand forecasting, interconnecting District Metered Areas (DMAs) to improve the forecasting capacity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Another application is the development of metamodels.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] To represent an image as a graph structure, the image is first divided into multiple patches, each of which is treated as a node in the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Edges are then formed by connecting each node to its nearest neighbors based on spatial or feature similarity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] This graph-based representation enables the application of graph learning models to visual tasks.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The relational structure helps to enhance feature extraction and improve performance on image understanding.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Graph-based representation of text helps to capture deeper semantic relationships between words.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Many studies have used graph networks to enhance performance in various text processing tasks such as text classification, question answering, Neural Machine Translation (NMT), event extraction, fact verification, etc.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GNNs have become a primary tool for modeling atomic interactions in computational chemistry and materials science, where molecules and crystal structures are naturally represented as graphs with atoms as nodes and chemical bonds or spatial proximity as edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] A key advantage over traditional quantum chemistry methods such as density functional theory (DFT) is the reduction in computational cost from O(n³) to O(n), enabling simulations at previously impractical scales.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Early GNN architectures for this domain include SchNet (2017), which introduced continuous-filter convolutional layers for learning on 3D molecular structures, and DimeNet (2020), which incorporated angular information between atoms to improve geometric expressivity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Subsequent equivariant architectures such as NequIP and MACE, which respect the rotational and translational symmetries of physical systems, achieved significant accuracy improvements on standard benchmarks including QM9, MD17, and the Materials Project.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Large open datasets have driven rapid progress in this area.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The Open Catalyst 2020 (OC20) dataset, comprising over 260 million DFT calculations of adsorbate-catalyst surface interactions, established a widely used benchmark for energy and force prediction tasks relevant to catalyst discovery.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] The Materials Project and Alexandria databases have similarly provided large-scale crystal structure data for training universal interatomic potentials.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] More recent datasets including OMat24 and OMol25 have extended coverage to organic molecules and complex materials at greater computational scale.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] These datasets have enabled the development of universal machine learning interatomic potentials (MLIPs) — models trained across diverse chemical domains rather than on system-specific data.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] Examples include CHGNet, M3GNet, MACE-MP, and Meta FAIR's Universal Models for Atoms (UMA), the latter trained on approximately 500 million atomic structures spanning molecules, materials, and catalysts.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-neural-network] GNoME, developed by Google DeepMind, applied GNNs to predict the stability of crystal structures, reporting the identification of millions of new stable candidate materials.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In mathematics and computer science, **graph theory** is the study of graphs, which are mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph in this context is made up of vertices (also called nodes or points) which are connected by edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A distinction is made between undirected graphs, where edges link two vertices symmetrically, and directed graphs, where edges link two vertices asymmetrically.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs are one of the principal objects of study in discrete mathematics.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph theory is a branch of mathematics that studies graphs, mathematical structures for modelling pairwise relations between objects.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] It is part of discrete mathematics, often considered part of combinatorics, although it is a stand-alone field due to its great growth and distinct from other fields, having its own kind of problems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The term "graph" was introduced by James Joseph Sylvester in a paper published in 1878 in *Nature*, where he drew an analogy between "quantic invariants" and "co-variants" of algebra and molecular diagrams.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The definition of a graph can vary, but one can understand that a graph is a structure consisting of vertices (also called nodes or points) and edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Two vertices of an edge are called the endpoints.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Occasionally, a graph is called an undirected graph, to distinguish it from a directed graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A directed graph is a graph where each edge has an assignment direction known as orientation, designated with an arrow.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A mixed graph can have edges that may be directed, and some may be undirected.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph can also be called a simple graph, to distinguish it from a multigraph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A multigraph allows many edges to have the same pair of endpoints, and it also allows an edge to connect a vertex to itself, known as a loop.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph can have its edges assigned a number, which is known as the weight.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Such a graph is called a weighted graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In 1736, Leonhard Euler published a paper titled *Solutio Problematis ad Geometriam Situs Pertinentis* on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, which is regarded as the first paper in the history of graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Euler's paper and Alexandre-Théophile Vandermonde's 1771 *Remarques sur les Problèmes de Situation* paper on the knight's tour carried on with the *analysis situs*, initiated by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Euler's characteristic relating the number of edges, vertices, and faces of a convex polyhedron was studied and generalized by Augustin-Louis Cauchy and Simon Antoine Jean L'Huilier, and represents the beginning of the branch of mathematics known as topology.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] More than one century after Euler's paper on the bridges of Königsberg, and while Johann Benedict Listing was introducing the concept of topology, Arthur Cayley was led by an interest in particular analytical forms arising from differential calculus to study a particular class of graphs, the trees.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This study had many implications for theoretical chemistry.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The techniques he used mainly concern the enumeration of graphs with particular properties.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Enumerative graph theory then arose from the results of Cayley and the fundamental results published by Pólya between 1935 and 1937.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] These were generalized by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn in 1959.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Cayley linked his results on trees with contemporary studies of chemical composition.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The fusion of ideas from mathematics with those from chemistry began what has become part of the standard terminology of graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The autonomous development of topology from 1860 to 1930 fertilized graph theory back through the works of Camille Jordan, Kazimierz Kuratowski, and Hassler Whitney.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Another important factor in the common development of graph theory and topology came from the use of the techniques of modern algebra.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The first example of such a use comes from the work of the physicist Gustav Kirchhoff, who published in 1845 his Kirchhoff's circuit laws for calculating the voltage and current in electric circuits.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The first textbook on graph theory was written by Dénes Kőnig, and published in 1936.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Another book by Frank Harary, published in 1969, was "considered the world over to be the definitive textbook on the subject", and enabled mathematicians, chemists, electrical engineers and social scientists to talk to each other.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Harary donated all of the royalties to fund the Pólya Prize.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] One of the most famous problems in graph theory is the four color problem: Is it true that any map drawn in the plane may have its regions colored with four colors, in such a way that any two regions having a common border have different colors?
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This problem was first posed by Francis Guthrie in 1852, and its first written record is in a letter of Augustus De Morgan addressed to William Rowan Hamilton the same year.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Many incorrect proofs have been proposed, including those by Augustin Cayley, Alfred Kempe, and others.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The study and the generalization of this problem by Peter Tait, Percy John Heawood, Frank P.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Ramsey and Hadwiger led to the study of the colorings of the graphs embedded on surfaces with arbitrary genus.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Tait's reformulation generated a new class of problems, the *factorization problems*, particularly studied by Petersen and Dénes Kőnig.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The works of Ramsey on colorations, and more specially, the results obtained by Pál Turán in 1941, were at the origin of another branch of graph theory, known as extremal graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The four-color problem remained unsolved for more than a century.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In 1969, Heinrich Heesch published a method for solving the problem using computers.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A computer-aided proof produced in 1976 by Kenneth Appel and Wolfgang Haken makes fundamental use of the notion of "discharging" developed by Heesch.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The proof involved checking the properties of 1,936 configurations by computer, and was not fully accepted at the time due to its complexity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A simpler proof considering only 633 configurations was given twenty years later by Robertson, Seymour, Sanders and Thomas.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The introduction of probabilistic methods in graph theory, especially in the study of Erdős and Rényi of the asymptotic probability of graph connectivity, gave rise to yet another branch, known as random graph theory, which has been a fruitful source of graph-theoretic results.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs related to topology.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs as topological spaces.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The graph in a topology is a set of simplexes that is called the simplicial one-dimensional complex.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This subarea studies the embedding (or imbedding) of a graph in surface and linkless embedding, graph minors, crossing number, map coloring, and voltage graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The embedding of a graph in a surface is the representation of a graph in which the points are associated with the vertices and simple arcs with edges in a surface.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The endpoints are associated with an edge, and the points with the end vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] No arcs include points associated with other vertices, and two arcs never intersect at a point that is interior to either of the arcs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The graph embedding can be generalized into the linkless embedding, whereby no two cycles of the graph are linked in three-dimensional Euclidean space, and a book, a collection of half-planes all having the same line as their boundary.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The graph is said to be minor if it can be formed from another graph by deleting vertices and edges, and by edge-contraction.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The earliest result of the graph minor theory is from Wagner's theorem, stating that a finite graph is planar if and only if its minor includes neither the complete graph on five vertices $K_{5}$ nor the utility graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A related result is the Robertson–Seymour theorem, implying the existence of forbidden minor for every property of graphs preserved by deletions and edge contractions.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The crossing number tells the minimum number of crossing edges of a graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This study originated from a Hungarian mathematician Pál Turán who asked for a factory plan that minimized the number of crossings between tracks connecting brick kilns to storage sites.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This problem can be formalized as asking for the crossing number of a complete bipartite graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph coloring is a methodical assignment of labelling the elements of a graph, which is traditionally called colors.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In coloring, no two adjacent elements have the same color.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] It requires the minimum number of colors, which is known as the chromatic number.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Four-color theorem stated that no more than four colors are required to color the regions of any map so that no two adjacent regions have the same color; that is, no two regions share a common boundary.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This theorem is stronger than five-color theorem.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Relatedly, Earth–Moon problem is known for the nowadays open problem on extension of the planar map coloring problem, solved by the four-color theorem.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A voltage graph is a directed graph whose edges are labelled invertibly by elements of a group.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This graph concisely specifies the derived graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] It is also a common way to form a covering graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory is the study of graph theory that involves major branches of algebra.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Major branches of algebra that are used are linear algebra and group theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A study of graph theory using linear algebra is called spectral graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This study focuses on adjacency matrix, a matrix that represents the graph, and its spectrum, which focuses on the characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors of the given adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] It also focuses on the Laplacian matrix of a graph, which involves the degree matrix (a diagonal matrix that represents the degree of a vertex) and the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Group theory, particularly automorphism groups and geometric group theory, focuses on various families of graphs based on symmetry in algebraic graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Such a symmetry includes symmetric graphs, vertex-transitive graphs, edge-transitive graphs, distance-transitive graphs, distance-regular graphs, and strongly regular graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Frucht's theorem states that every finite group is the group of symmetries of a finite undirected graph, or more strongly, there exist infinitely many non-isomorphic simple connected graphs such that the automorphism group of each of them is isomorphic to a finite group.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory also studies the algebraic invariants, chromatic polynomial, Tutte polynomial of a graph, and knot invariant.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph invariant is a property of graphs that depends only on the abstract structure, instead of labellings or drawings of the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A chromatic polynomial is a polynomial that counts the number of graph colorings as a function of the number of colors.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The Tutte polynomial is a two-variable polynomial on graph connectivity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory studies a graph drawn with straight-line or continuous curved edges with geometric properties combinatorially.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory focuses on combinatorial and geometric properties of a graph that is drawn in a plane with straight-line or continuous curved edges in Euclidean space.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] As part of discrete geometry and computational geometry, geometric graph theory studies planar graphs, relationship to higher-dimensional convex polytopes, intersection of geometrical shaped sets, and other geometries' subareas of incidence geometry and projective geometry.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A planar graph wherein its vertices are embedded as points, and its edges are non-crossing line segments in the Euclidean plane is called planar straight-line graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Any planar graph can be represented as a planar straight-line graph by Fáry's theorem.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The planar straight-line graph is the special case of a Euclidean graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The Euclidean graph allows its edges to have the length of the Euclidean distance between its endpoints.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A visibility graph is a graph whose vertices and edges are the point locations and visible connections, respectively.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In a simple polygon, where its edges are not self-intersecting and have no holes, the vertices of a visibility graph are connected by edges that represent the sides and diagonals of a polygon.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The vertices are defined as the point locations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Polyhedral graph is an undirected graph that forms the vertices and edges of a three-dimensional convex polyhedron.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In order to achieve it, such a graph must meet the requirements of Steinitz's theorem, stating that every convex polyhedron is 3-vertex connected planar graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The planar graph remains connected whenever any two of its vertices are removed.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] An intersection graph is a graph in which each vertex is associated with a set and in which vertices are connected by edges whenever the corresponding sets have a nonempty intersection.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Each vertex is represented as a set, and every two vertices are connected.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Hence, the intersection graph of finite sets can be represented through the smallest number of required elements, known as the intersection number.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The result graph can be geometric whenever the sets are geometrical objects.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] For instance, the intersection graph of line segments in one dimension is an interval graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The intersection graph of unit disks in the plane is a unit disk graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The intersection of a circle packing is a coin graph, where a vertex and an edge represent a circle and every pair of tangent circles; by Koebe–Andreev–Thurston theorem, the intersection graphs of non-crossing circles are exactly the planar graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Scheinerman's theorem states that every planar graph can be represented as the intersection graph of line segments in the plane.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The Levi graph is a bipartite graph that associates to the incidence structure and projective configuration.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] By applying to information visualization, this creates another subarea of graph theory that is known as graph drawing, which visualizes a graph depiction.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Frequently drawn as node–link diagrams, the vertices of a graph are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels, and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Many definitions for graph drawings based on quality measures include the crossing number, area, symmetry display on finding the problem of a graph's group automorphism, bend minimization, angular resolution, and slope number.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Tools for graph drawings are the circle packing, the intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory is a branch of mathematics at the intersection of extremal combinatorics and graph theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This area studies the maximum number of a graph's edges, known as the extremal number.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The subarea's milestone originated from Mantel's theorem on the extremal number of a triangle-free graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Turán's theorem extended Mantel's theorem for any undirected graph that does not have a complete subgraph of a given size.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Turán's theorem is generalized by Erdős–Stone theorem, which is occasionally known as the "fundamental theorem of extremal graph theory".
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory also studies forbidden subgraph problem, homomorphism density, and Szemerédi regularity lemma.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The forbidden subgraphs problem suggests finding the extremal number of a graph with n vertices such that it does not have a subgraph that is isomorphic to the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A homomorphism density is a parameter that involves the graph homomorphism.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The density may refer to the probability that a map from the vertices of a graph to the vertices of another one chosen uniformly at random is a graph homomorphism.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Being homomorphic means there exists a mapping between two graphs that respects their structure, or equivalently, a function between the vertex sets of two graphs that maps adjacent vertices to adjacent vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Szemerédi's regularity lemma states that a graph can be partitioned into a bounded number of parts so that the edges between parts are $\varepsilon$ -regular.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The theory of random graph focuses on graphs using probabilistic method.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The subarea was founded by Hungarian mathematicians Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi, whose modelling generates random graphs, known as Erdős–Rényi model.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A tree is an undirected graph where every pair of vertices is connected by exactly one path.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Therefore, a random tree is a tree that is formed by a stochastic process.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs can be used to model many types of relations and processes in physical, biological, social and information systems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Many practical problems can be represented by graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Emphasizing their application to real-world systems, the term *network* is sometimes defined to mean a graph in which attributes (e.g. names) are associated with the vertices and edges, and the subject that expresses and understands real-world systems as a network is called network science.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Within computer science, 'causal' and 'non-causal' linked structures are graphs that are used to represent networks of communication, data organization, computational devices, the flow of computation, etc.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] For instance, the link structure of a website can be represented by a directed graph, in which the vertices (nodes) represent web pages and directed edges represent links from one page to another.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A similar approach can be taken to problems in social media, travel, biology, computer chip design, mapping the progression of neuro-degenerative diseases, and many other fields.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The development of algorithms to handle graphs is therefore of major interest in computer science.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The transformation of graphs is often formalized and represented by graph rewrite systems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Complementary to graph transformation systems focusing on rule-based in-memory manipulation of graphs are graph databases geared towards transaction-safe, persistent storing and querying of graph-structured data.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph-theoretic methods, in various forms, have proven particularly useful in linguistics, since natural language often lends itself well to discrete structure.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Traditionally, syntax and compositional semantics follow tree-based structures, whose expressive power lies in the principle of compositionality, modeled in a hierarchical graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] More contemporary approaches such as head-driven phrase structure grammar model the syntax of natural language using typed feature structures, which are directed acyclic graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Within lexical semantics, especially as applied to computers, modeling word meaning is easier when a given word is understood in terms of related words; semantic networks are therefore important in computational linguistics.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Still, other methods in phonology (e.g. optimality theory, which uses lattice graphs) and morphology (e.g. finite-state morphology, using finite-state transducers) are common in the analysis of language as a graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Indeed, the usefulness of this area of mathematics to linguistics has borne organizations such as TextGraphs, as well as various 'Net' projects, such as WordNet, VerbNet, and others.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used to study molecules in chemistry and physics.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In condensed matter physics, the three-dimensional structure of complicated simulated atomic structures can be studied quantitatively by gathering statistics on graph-theoretic properties related to the topology of the atoms.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Also, "the Feynman graphs and rules of calculation summarize quantum field theory in a form in close contact with the experimental numbers one wants to understand." In chemistry a graph makes a natural model for a molecule, where vertices represent atoms and edges bonds.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This approach is especially used in computer processing of molecular structures, ranging from chemical editors to database searching.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In statistical physics, graphs can represent local connections between interacting parts of a system, as well as the dynamics of a physical process on such systems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Similarly, in computational neuroscience graphs can be used to represent functional connections between brain areas that interact to give rise to various cognitive processes, where the vertices represent different areas of the brain and the edges represent the connections between those areas.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph theory plays an important role in electrical modeling of electrical networks, here, weights are associated with resistance of the wire segments to obtain electrical properties of network structures.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs are also used to represent the micro-scale channels of porous media, in which the vertices represent the pores and the edges represent the smaller channels connecting the pores.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Chemical graph theory uses the molecular graph as a means to model molecules.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs and networks are excellent models to study and understand phase transitions and critical phenomena.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Removal of nodes or edges leads to a critical transition where the network breaks into small clusters which is studied as a phase transition.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This breakdown is studied via percolation theory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph theory is also widely used in sociology as a way, for example, to measure actors' prestige or to explore rumor spreading, notably through the use of social network analysis software.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Under the umbrella of social networks are many different types of graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Acquaintanceship and friendship graphs describe whether people know each other.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Influence graphs model whether certain people can influence the behavior of others.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Finally, collaboration graphs model whether two people work together in a particular way, such as acting in a movie together.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Likewise, graph theory is useful in biology and conservation efforts where a vertex can represent regions where certain species exist (or inhabit) and the edges represent migration paths or movement between the regions.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] This information is important when looking at breeding patterns or tracking the spread of disease, parasites or how changes to the movement can affect other species.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs are also commonly used in molecular biology and genomics to model and analyze datasets with complex relationships.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] For example, graph-based methods are often used to 'cluster' cells together into cell-types in single-cell transcriptome analysis.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Another use is to model genes or proteins in a pathway and study the relationships between them, such as metabolic pathways and gene regulatory networks.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Evolutionary trees, ecological networks, and hierarchical clustering of gene expression patterns are also represented as graph structures.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used in connectomics; nervous systems can be seen as a graph, where the nodes are neurons and the edges are the connections between them.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph structure can be extended by assigning a weight to each edge of the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs with weights, or weighted graphs, are used to represent structures in which pairwise connections have some numerical values.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] For example, if a graph represents a road network, the weights could represent the length of each road.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] There may be several weights associated with each edge, including distance (as in the previous example), travel time, or monetary cost.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Such weighted graphs are commonly used to program GPS's, and travel-planning search engines that compare flight times and costs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph is an abstraction of relationships that emerge in nature; hence, it cannot be coupled to a certain representation.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The way it is represented depends on the degree of convenience such representation provides for a certain application.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The most common representations are the visual, in which, usually, vertices are drawn and connected by edges, and the tabular, in which rows of a table provide information about the relationships between the vertices within the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graphs are usually represented visually by drawing a point or circle for every vertex, and drawing a line between two vertices if they are connected by an edge.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] If the graph is directed, the direction is indicated by drawing an arrow.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] If the graph is weighted, the weight is added on the arrow.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A graph drawing should not be confused with the graph itself (the abstract, non-visual structure) as there are several ways to structure the graph drawing.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] All that matters is which vertices are connected to which others by how many edges and not the exact layout.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In practice, it is often difficult to decide if two drawings represent the same graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Depending on the problem domain some layouts may be better suited and easier to understand than others.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Tutte was very influential on the subject of graph drawing.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Among other achievements, he introduced the use of linear algebraic methods to obtain graph drawings.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Graph drawing also can be said to encompass problems that deal with the crossing number and its various generalizations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The crossing number of a graph is the minimum number of intersections between edges that a drawing of the graph in the plane must contain.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] For a planar graph, the crossing number is zero by definition.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Drawings on surfaces other than the plane are also studied.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] There are other techniques to visualize a graph away from vertices and edges, including circle packings, intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The tabular representation lends itself well to computational applications.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] There are different ways to store graphs in a computer system.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The data structure used depends on both the graph structure and the algorithm used for manipulating the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Theoretically one can distinguish between list and matrix structures but in concrete applications the best structure is often a combination of both.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] List structures are often preferred for sparse graphs as they have smaller memory requirements.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Matrix structures on the other hand provide faster access for some applications but can consume huge amounts of memory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Implementations of sparse matrix structures that are efficient on modern parallel computer architectures are an object of current investigation.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] List structures include the edge list, an array of pairs of vertices, and the adjacency list, which separately lists the neighbors of each vertex: Much like the edge list, each vertex has a list of which vertices it is adjacent to.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Matrix structures include the incidence matrix, a matrix of 0's and 1's whose rows represent vertices and whose columns represent edges, and the adjacency matrix, in which both the rows and columns are indexed by vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In both cases a 1 indicates two adjacent objects and a 0 indicates two non-adjacent objects.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The degree matrix indicates the degree of vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The Laplacian matrix is a modified form of the adjacency matrix that incorporates information about the degrees of the vertices, and is useful in some calculations such as Kirchhoff's theorem on the number of spanning trees of a graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The distance matrix, like the adjacency matrix, has both its rows and columns indexed by vertices, but rather than containing a 0 or a 1 in each cell it contains the length of a shortest path between two vertices.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] There is a large literature on graphical enumeration: the problem of counting graphs meeting specified conditions.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Some of this work is found in Harary and Palmer (1973).
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A common problem, called the subgraph isomorphism problem, is finding a fixed graph as a subgraph in a given graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] One reason to be interested in such a question is that many graph properties are *hereditary* for subgraphs, which means that a graph has the property if and only if all subgraphs have it too.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Finding maximal subgraphs of a certain kind is often an NP-complete problem.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] One special case of subgraph isomorphism is the graph isomorphism problem.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] It asks whether two graphs are isomorphic.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] It is not known whether this problem is NP-complete, nor whether it can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A similar problem is finding induced subgraphs in a given graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Again, some important graph properties are hereditary with respect to induced subgraphs, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all induced subgraphs also have it.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Finding maximal induced subgraphs of a certain kind is also often NP-complete.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Still another such problem, the minor containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a minor of a given graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A minor or subcontraction of a graph is any graph obtained by taking a subgraph and contracting some (or no) edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Many graph properties are hereditary for minors, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all minors have it too.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A similar problem, the subdivision containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a subdivision of a given graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] A subdivision or homeomorphism of a graph is any graph obtained by subdividing some (or no) edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Subdivision containment is related to graph properties such as planarity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Another class of problems has to do with the extent to which various species and generalizations of graphs are determined by their *point-deleted subgraphs*.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Many problems and theorems in graph theory have to do with various ways of coloring graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Typically, one is interested in coloring a graph so that no two adjacent vertices have the same color, or with other similar restrictions.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] One may also consider coloring edges (possibly so that no two coincident edges are the same color), or other variations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Constraint modeling theories concern families of directed graphs related by a partial order.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] In these applications, graphs are ordered by specificity, meaning that more constrained graphs—which are more specific and thus contain a greater amount of information—are subsumed by those that are more general.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Operations between graphs include evaluating the direction of a subsumption relationship between two graphs, if any, and computing graph unification.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] The unification of two argument graphs is defined as the most general graph (or the computation thereof) that is consistent with (i.e. contains all of the information in) the inputs, if such a graph exists; efficient unification algorithms are known.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] For constraint frameworks which are strictly compositional, graph unification is the sufficient satisfiability and combination function.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Well-known applications include automatic theorem proving and modeling the elaboration of linguistic structure.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Covering problems in graphs may refer to various set cover problems on subsets of vertices/subgraphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Decomposition, defined as partitioning the edge set of a graph (with as many vertices as necessary accompanying the edges of each part of the partition), has a wide variety of questions.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Often, the problem is to decompose a graph into subgraphs isomorphic to a fixed graph; for instance, decomposing a complete graph into Hamiltonian cycles.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Other problems specify a family of graphs into which a given graph should be decomposed, for instance, a family of cycles, or decomposing a complete graph *K**n* into *n* − 1 specified trees having, respectively, 1, 2, 3, ..., *n* − 1 edges.
[src:graph-neural-networks/graph-theory] Many problems involve characterizing the members of various classes of graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:graph-neural-networks/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In multivariate statistics, **spectral clustering** techniques make use of the spectrum (eigenvalues) of the similarity matrix of the data to perform dimensionality reduction before clustering in fewer dimensions.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The similarity matrix is provided as an input and consists of a quantitative assessment of the relative similarity of each pair of points in the dataset.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In application to image segmentation, spectral clustering is known as segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Given an enumerated set of data points, the similarity matrix may be defined as a symmetric matrix A , where $A_{ij}\geq 0$ represents a measure of the similarity between data points with indices i and j .
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The general approach to spectral clustering is to use a standard clustering method (there are many such methods, *k*-means is discussed below) on relevant eigenvectors of a Laplacian matrix of A .
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] There are many different ways to define a Laplacian which have different mathematical interpretations, and so the clustering will also have different interpretations.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The eigenvectors that are relevant are the ones that correspond to several smallest eigenvalues of the Laplacian except for the smallest eigenvalue which will have a value of 0.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] For computational efficiency, these eigenvectors are often computed as the eigenvectors corresponding to the largest several eigenvalues of a function of the Laplacian.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is well known to relate to partitioning of a mass-spring system, where each mass is associated with a data point and each spring stiffness corresponds to a weight of an edge describing a similarity of the two related data points, as in the spring system.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The goal of normalization is making the diagonal entries of the Laplacian matrix to be all unit, also scaling off-diagonal entries correspondingly.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In a weighted graph, a vertex may have a large degree because of a small number of connected edges but with large weights just as well as due to a large number of connected edges with unit weights.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] A popular normalized spectral clustering technique is the **normalized cuts algorithm** or *Shi–Malik algorithm* introduced by Jianbo Shi and Jitendra Malik, commonly used for image segmentation.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] and can also be used for spectral clustering.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] A mathematically equivalent algorithm takes the eigenvector u corresponding to the largest eigenvalue of the random walk normalized adjacency matrix $P=D^{-1}A$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Knowing the n -by- k matrix V of selected eigenvectors, mapping — called spectral embedding — of the original n data points is performed to a k -dimensional vector space using the rows of V .
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Now the analysis is reduced to clustering vectors with k components, which may be done in various ways.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In the simplest case $k=1$ , the selected single eigenvector v , called the Fiedler vector, corresponds to the second smallest eigenvalue.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Using the components of $v,$ one can place all points whose component in v is positive in the set $B_{+}$ and the rest in $B_{-}$ , thus bi-partitioning the graph and labeling the data points with two labels.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The algorithm can be used for hierarchical clustering by repeatedly partitioning the subsets in the same fashion.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In the general case $k>1$ , any vector clustering technique can be used, e.g., DBSCAN.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] For large-sized graphs, the second eigenvalue of the (normalized) graph Laplacian matrix is often ill-conditioned, leading to slow convergence of iterative eigenvalue solvers.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Preconditioning is a key technology accelerating the convergence, e.g., in the matrix-free LOBPCG method.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering has been successfully applied on large graphs by first identifying their community structure, and then clustering communities.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is closely related to nonlinear dimensionality reduction, and dimension reduction techniques such as locally-linear embedding can be used to reduce errors from noise or outliers.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Denoting the number of the data points by n , it is important to estimate the memory footprint and compute time, or number of arithmetic operations (AO) performed, as a function of n .
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] No matter the algorithm of the spectral clustering, the two main costly items are the construction of the graph Laplacian and determining its k eigenvectors for the spectral embedding.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The last step — determining the labels from the n -by- k matrix of eigenvectors — is typically the least expensive requiring only $kn$ AO and creating just a n -by- 1 vector of the labels in memory.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The need to construct the graph Laplacian is common for all distance- or correlation-based clustering methods.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Computing the eigenvectors is specific to spectral clustering only.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The graph Laplacian can be and commonly is constructed from the adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The construction can be performed matrix-free, i.e., without explicitly forming the matrix of the graph Laplacian and no AO.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] It can also be performed in-place of the adjacency matrix without increasing the memory footprint.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Either way, the costs of constructing the graph Laplacian is essentially determined by the costs of constructing the n -by- n graph adjacency matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Moreover, a normalized Laplacian has exactly the same eigenvectors as the normalized adjacency matrix, but with the order of the eigenvalues reversed.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Thus, instead of computing the eigenvectors corresponding to the smallest eigenvalues of the normalized Laplacian, one can equivalently compute the eigenvectors corresponding to the largest eigenvalues of the normalized adjacency matrix, without even talking about the Laplacian matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Naive constructions of the graph adjacency matrix, e.g., using the RBF kernel, make it dense, thus requiring $n^{2}$ memory and $n^{2}$ AO to determine each of the $n^{2}$ entries of the matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Nystrom method can be used to approximate the similarity matrix, but the approximate matrix is not elementwise positive, i.e. cannot be interpreted as a distance-based similarity.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Algorithms to construct the graph adjacency matrix as a sparse matrix are typically based on a nearest neighbor search, which estimate or sample a neighborhood of a given data point for nearest neighbors, and compute non-zero entries of the adjacency matrix by comparing only pairs of the neighbors.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The cost of computing the n -by- k (with $k\ll n$ ) matrix of selected eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian is normally proportional to the cost of multiplication of the n -by- n graph Laplacian matrix by a vector, which varies greatly whether the graph Laplacian matrix is dense or sparse.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] For the dense case the cost thus is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The very commonly cited in the literature cost $O(n^{3})$ comes from choosing $k=n$ and is clearly misleading, since, e.g., in a hierarchical spectral clustering $k=1$ as determined by the Fiedler vector.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Moreover, matrix-free eigenvalue solvers such as LOBPCG can efficiently run in parallel, e.g., on multiple GPUs with distributed memory, resulting not only in high quality clusters, which spectral clustering is famous for, but also top performance.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Free software implementing spectral clustering is available in large open source projects like scikit-learn using LOBPCG with multigrid preconditioning or ARPACK, MLlib for pseudo-eigenvector clustering using the power iteration method, and R.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The ideas behind spectral clustering may not be immediately obvious.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] It may be useful to highlight relationships with other methods.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In particular, it can be described in the context of kernel clustering methods, which reveals several similarities with other approaches.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is closely related to the **k-means** algorithm, especially in how cluster assignments are ultimately made.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Although the two methods differ fundamentally in their initial formulations—spectral clustering being graph-based and k-means being centroid-based—the connection becomes clear when spectral clustering is viewed through the lens of **kernel methods**.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In particular, **weighted kernel k-means** provides a key theoretical bridge between the two.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Kernel k-means is a generalization of the standard k-means algorithm, where data is implicitly mapped into a high-dimensional feature space through a kernel function, and clustering is performed in that space.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering, especially the normalized versions, performs a similar operation by mapping the input data (or graph nodes) to a lower-dimensional space defined by the **eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian**.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] These eigenvectors correspond to the solution of a **relaxation** of the **normalized cut** or other graph partitioning objectives.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Mathematically, the objective function minimized by spectral clustering can be shown to be equivalent to the objective function of weighted kernel k-means in this transformed space.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] This was formally established in works such as where they demonstrated that normalized cuts are equivalent to a weighted version of kernel k-means applied to the rows of the normalized Laplacian’s eigenvector matrix.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Because of this equivalence, **spectral clustering can be viewed as performing kernel k-means in the eigenspace defined by the graph Laplacian**.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] This theoretical insight has practical implications: the final clustering step in spectral clustering typically involves running the **standard k-means algorithm** on the rows of the matrix formed by the first k eigenvectors of the Laplacian.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] These rows can be thought of as embedding each data point or node in a low-dimensional space where the clusters are more well-separated and hence, easier for k-means to detect.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Additionally, **multi-level methods** have been developed to directly optimize this shared objective function.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] These methods work by iteratively **coarsening** the graph to reduce problem size, solving the problem on a coarse graph, and then **refining** the solution on successively finer graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] This leads to more efficient optimization for large-scale problems, while still capturing the global structure preserved by the spectral embedding.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is also conceptually related to **DBSCAN** (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise), particularly in the special case where the spectral method is used to identify **connected graph components** of a graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] In this trivial case—where the goal is to identify subsets of nodes with **no interconnecting edges** between them—the spectral method effectively reduces to a connectivity-based clustering approach, much like DBSCAN.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] DBSCAN operates by identifying **density-connected regions** in the input space: points that are reachable from one another via a sequence of neighboring points within a specified radius (ε), and containing a minimum number of points (minPts).
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The algorithm excels at discovering clusters of arbitrary shape and separating out noise without needing to specify the number of clusters in advance.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] This mirrors DBSCAN's ability to isolate **density-connected components**.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] The zeroth eigenvectors of the unnormalized Laplacian correspond to these components, with one eigenvector per connected region.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Therefore, spectral clustering in this regime behaves like a **spectral version of DBSCAN**, especially in sparse graphs or when constructing ε-neighborhood graphs.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] While DBSCAN operates directly in the data space using density estimates, spectral clustering transforms the data into an eigenspace where **global structure and connectivity** are emphasized.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Both methods are non-parametric in spirit, and neither assumes convex cluster shapes, which further supports their conceptual alignment.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Ravi Kannan, Santosh Vempala and Adrian Vetta proposed a bicriteria measure to define the quality of a given clustering.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] They said that a clustering was an (α, ε)-clustering if the conductance of each cluster (in the clustering) was at least α and the weight of the inter-cluster edges was at most ε fraction of the total weight of all the edges in the graph.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] They also look at two approximation algorithms in the same paper.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering as a machine learning method was popularized by Shi & Malik and Ng, Jordan, & Weiss.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] Ideas and network measures related to spectral clustering also play an important role in a number of applications apparently different from clustering problems.
[src:graph-neural-networks/spectral-clustering] For instance, networks with stronger spectral partitions take longer to converge in opinion-updating models used in sociology and economics.
